value.value: Trauma to the conjunctiva of the eye.
Trauma to the cornea of the eye.
Any anatomic abnormality or physiologic dysfunction of the lens of the eye that is present at the time of birth.
A form of glaucoma in which there is no visible abnormality in the trabecular meshwork.
Trauma to the larynx.

Pneumonia caused by the parasite Toxoplasma gondii.  It usually presents as an opportunistic infection in immunocompromised patients, especially patients with AIDS.  It is rare in immunocompetent individuals.  Signs and symptoms include cough, fever, and dyspnea.
Pneumoconiosis caused by exposure to slate dust.

label.value: Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads III, aVF and often II, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the inferior wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

label.value: Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, and upright T wave, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the posterior wall of the left ventricle. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present. (CDISC)

A third generation semisynthetic cephalosporin antibiotic with bactericidal activity. Cefotaxime inhibits mucopeptide synthesis by binding to and inactivating penicillin binding proteins thereby interfering with the final transpeptidation step required for cross-linking of peptidoglycan units which are a component of bacterial cell walls. This results in a reduction of cell wall stability and causes cell lysis.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the maxillary sinus.
A history of myocardial infarction in the absence of clinical symptoms and positive electrocardiographic findings.
Damage to an artery from traumatic or pathologic processes.
Inflammation of the colon that is caused by Cytomegalovirus.
A concretion in the pancreatic duct.
A non-neoplastic proliferation of morphologically bland C-cells with a diffuse growth pattern in the thyroid gland.
A congenital or acquired hyperplasia of the cells of the adrenal cortex or medulla.
An abnormal growth in the adrenal gland.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the ethmoid sinus.
An overwhelming, irrational, and persistent fear of traveling in an aircraft.
A congenital defect in which the vagina is underdeveloped.

label.value: Mixed Tumor of the Parotid Gland

value.value: A benign or malignant neoplasm that arises from the parotid gland.  It is characterized by the presence of epithelial and mesenchymal elements.  This category includes pleomorphic adenoma, carcinoma ex pleomorphic adenoma, and carcinosarcoma.

A carcinoma that arises from the intrahepatic bile duct epithelium in any site of the intrahepatic biliary tree.  Grossly, the malignant lesions are solid, nodular, and grayish.  Morphologically, the vast majority of cases are adenocarcinomas.  Signs and symptoms include malaise, weight loss, right upper quadrant abdominal pain, and night sweats.  Early detection is difficult and the prognosis is generally poor.
A benign adipose tissue neoplasm of the axilla.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the frontal sinus.

An anxiety disorder characterized by an intense, irrational fear of an object, activity, or situation. The individual seeks to avoid the object, activity, or situation. In adults, the individual recognizes that the fear is excessive or unreasonable.
Insomnia as a result of an extrinsic cause.
Trauma to the anus.
A hyperplasia characterized by excessive proliferation of endometrial cells, resulting in the formation of complex epithelial structures.  Epithelial atypia may be present or absent.

Transformation of chronic lymphocytic leukemia into aggressive non-Hodgkin lymphoma, usually diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (immunoblastic or centroblastic variant).  Occasional cases of transformation to Hodgkin lymphoma have also been described, particularly in patients treated with purine nucleotide analogues.  Molecular genetic studies suggest that in approximately half of the cases, the lymphoma is clonally related to the underlying chronic lymphocytic leukemia, whereas in the remaining cases the lymphoma probably represents a secondary, unrelated neoplasm.

label.value: Splenic Lymphoma with Circulating Villous Lymphocytes

value.value: An overwhelming, irrational, and persistent fear of taking and failing tests.

label.value: Malignant Neoplasm of Multiple Primary Sites

value.value: A malignant neoplasm arising in multiple primary sites.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the sphenoid sinus.

label.value: Acute Gonococcal Infection of Upper Genitourinary Tract

value.value: A gonococcal infection of the upper urinary tract that is rapid in onset.

Acute inflammation of the endocardium. Bacteria is the usual etiologic agent, and the distinction between "acute" and "subacute" has traditionally been made based on the pathogenic organism and clinical presentation.

label.value: Polycythaemia due to Excess Erythropoetin Production

value.value: Polycythemia that is caused by excess erythropoietin.
Increasing girth of the mid section of an individual.
